article.description:
Alana Beard scored 22 points, Chasity Melvin
had 14, and the Washington Mystics made all 18 free throws Tuesday
night in a 93-79 victory over the Houston Comets, who played
without reigning MVP Sheryl Swoopes.
article.headline: Beard, Melvin helps Mystics bring Comets back to earth
article.linkText: Beard, Melvin helps Mystics bring Comets back to earth
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Washington Mystics were again scoring
points at a record pace, and one of the league's top coaches
couldn't do anything about it.

Alana Beard scored 22 points, Chasity Melvin had 14, and the
Mystics made all 18 free throws Tuesday night in a 93-79 victory
over the Houston Comets, who played without reigning MVP Sheryl
Swoopes.

The Mystics, taking advantage of the WNBA's new 24-second clock,
tied a franchise record with their fourth 90-point game of the
season -- and they've only played five. Their 86.6-per-game average
is tops in the league and on pace to shatter the WNBA record of
77.3 set by the 2000 Comets.

"We just couldn't stop them," Houston coach Van Chancellor
said. "We did everything we could. We switched defenses. We went
from man to zone. We went from every combination. I substituted. I
played everybody I had. I just couldn't find anything that could
stop them. They shot and executed offensively as well as any team
I've seen in a long, long time."

Beard went 8-for-13 from the field and 5-for-5 from the line.
Nikki Teasley matched her season high with 11 points and had a
season-high 11 assists. DeLisha Milton-Jones scored 12 points, and
Crystal Robinson had four steals for the Mystics, who improved to
4-0 at home and moved into a tie with Connecticut atop the Eastern
Conference standings. The 93 points were the most ever scored
against Houston.

"You're only seeing probably 50 percent of what we can do,"
Beard said.

Second-year forward Roneeka Hodges, making her first career
start, scored a career-high 21 points, and Tina Thompson added 19
for the Comets, who had a five-game winning streak snapped. Houston
couldn't overcome the absence of three-time league MVP Swoopes, who
left Sunday's victory over Minnesota with a sore back and didn't
travel with the team.

"You can't miss one of the premier defensive players in this
league for the last 10 years and not have that affect you,"
Chancellor said. "But I don't think that would have meant the
difference in the game. I don't think she could have guarded
Milton, Robinson, Melvin, Beard and Teasley at the same time."

The Mystics were happy not to deal with Swoopes, who will be
re-evaluated before Friday's home game against New York.

"We got a break tonight," Washington coach Richie Adubato
said. "I'll take it any time we can get it."

The Mystics never trailed. Beard made her first five shots to
help build a 31-24 first-quarter lead. A 12-4 run pushed the lead
to 15 late in the first half, and the score was 55-44 at halftime.

The Comets opened the second half with a 6-0 run, but Teasley
answered with a 3-pointer. Beard later converted a three-point play
and made a fast-break layup in an 8-0 spurt that put the Mystics
back in control.

The only downside for the Mystics was the season-low 5,897 fans
at the Verizon Center, a sobering stat for a franchise that once
regularly led the league in attendance.

"Hopefully by us going out and putting up the scores and
playing defense the way we can play, we can get our fans back,"
Beard said.
